question.title: AndroidAnnotations with Spring Rest Template does not work when obfuscated

node.contents: My Android application uses AndroidAnnotations and Spring Rest Template. When creating a debug build, it runs fine. When I create a release build however, the REST call does not work. Below are some relevant snippets from my code and build configuration.

astNode.text: My Android application uses AndroidAnnotations and Spring Rest Template. When creating a debug build, it runs fine. When I create a release build however, the REST call does not work. Below are some relevant snippets from my code and build configuration.

elements.contents: public class MyActivity extends Activity { @Bean protected MyService myService; @Background protected void fetchData() { try { data = myService.getData(); } catch (DataAccessException dae) { Log.e(getClass().getSimpleName(), dae.getMessage(), dae); } } }

units.rawText: public class MyActivity extends Activity { @Bean protected MyService myService; @Background protected void fetchData() { try { data = myService.getData(); } catch (DataAccessException dae) { Log.e(getClass().getSimpleName(), dae.getMessage(), dae); } } }

elements.contents: @EBean public class MyService { @RestService protected MyRestClient myRestClient; public Data getData() { return myRestClient.getData(); } }

units.rawText: @EBean public class MyService { @RestService protected MyRestClient myRestClient; public Data getData() { return myRestClient.getData(); } }

elements.contents: @Rest(converters = { GsonHttpMessageConverter.class }, interceptors = { AuthenticationInterceptor.class, UserAgentInterceptor.class }, rootUrl = "https://myhost/rest") public interface MyShiftRestClient { @Get("/data") Data getData(); }

units.rawText: @Rest(converters = { GsonHttpMessageConverter.class }, interceptors = { AuthenticationInterceptor.class, UserAgentInterceptor.class }, rootUrl = "https://myhost/rest") public interface MyShiftRestClient { @Get("/data") Data getData(); }

elements.contents: -dontwarn org.apache.http.annotation.Immutable -dontwarn org.apache.http.annotation.NotThreadSafe -dontwarn org.springframework.** -keep class com.mypackage.** { public protected private *; } -keepclassmembers public class org.springframework.** { public *; }

node.contents: When running the obfuscated app, the Data object that is returned by MyRestClient is an empty object, i.e. it is initialised but none of its instance variables have any values. I guess it has to do with my ProGuard configuration, that's why I added the last configuration statement, but it had no effect. There is no Exception being logged.

astNode.text: When running the obfuscated app, the Data object that is returned by MyRestClient is an empty object, i.e. it is initialised but none of its instance variables have any values. I guess it has to do with my ProGuard configuration, that's why I added the last configuration statement, but it had no effect. There is no Exception being logged.

node.contents: The `Data` class is in a `com.mypackage.model` package, and thus excluded from ProGuard. I checked with dex2jar and JAD and the class is untouched.

astNode.text: The `Data` class is in a `com.mypackage.model` package, and thus excluded from ProGuard. I checked with dex2jar and JAD and the class is untouched.

node.contents: I don't know what's the problem but try to exclude the Gson packages (com.google.gson) too from ProGuard.

astNode.text: I don't know what's the problem but try to exclude the Gson packages (com.google.gson) too from ProGuard.

node.contents: Well, that more-or-less did the trick, after excluding `sun.misc.Unsafe` as well. See the [example ProGuard config for GSON](https://code.google.com/p/google-gson/source/browse/trunk/examples/android-proguard-example/proguard.cfg) for reference.

node.contents: Try to keep members of Data class too. Data class properties must be untouched to allow Gson converter fill it, as it is done based on property names.
